ed to treat a variety of specific conditions, such as headaches, back pain, and insomnia.\n\n**Snehana** is a type of Ayurvedic treatment that involves applying medicated oil to the body. It is believed to nourish the tissues, improve circulation, and reduce inflammation. Snehana can be used to treat a variety of conditions, such as dry skin, eczema, and arthritis.\n\n**Deepaka** is a type of Ayurvedic treatment that involves applying heat to the body. It is believed to improve circulation, reduce inflammation, and promote sweating. Deepaka can be used to treat a variety of conditions, such as colds, flu, and bronchitis.\n\n**Taila Paatra** is a type of Ayurvedic instrument that is used to apply oil to the body. It is typically made of metal or glass and has a spout that allows for precise application.\n\n**Vastra Gun`a** refers to the qualities of the cloth that is used for Abhyanga. The cloth should be soft, absorbent, and comfortable to wear.\n\n**Drava Gun`a** refers to the qualities of the oil that is used for Abhyanga. The oil should be warm, nourishing, and appropriate for the individual's constitution.\n\n**Snigdha Gun`a** refers to the oily or unctuous quality of the oil that is used for Abhyanga. The oil should be able to penetrate the skin and nourish the tissues.\n\n**Sookshma Gun`a** refers to the fine or subtle quality of the oil that is used for Abhyanga. The oil should be able to penetrate the skin and reach the deeper tissues.\n\n**Sthira Gun`a** refers to the stable or firm quality of the oil that is used for Abhyanga. The oil should not be too thin or too thick, and it should be able to stay on the skin for a period of time.\n\n**Ushn`a Karma** refers to the heating effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to improve circulation and reduce inflammation.\n\n**Balya Karma** refers to the strengthening effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to strengthen the muscles and joints, and it can also improve overall vitality.\n\n**Jvarahara Karma** refers to the fever-reducing effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to reduce fever by promoting sweating.\n\n**Maardavakara Karma** refers to the softening effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to soften the skin and reduce dryness.\n\n**Nidraakara Karma** refers to the sleep-inducing effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to promote relaxation and sleep.\n\n**Preen`ana Karma** refers to the pleasure-giving effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to improve mood and promote a sense of well-being.\n\n**Pusht`ikrit Karma** refers to the nourishing effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to nourish the tissues and improve overall health.\n\n**S`hramahara Karma** refers to the fatigue-reducing effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to reduce fatigue and improve energy levels.\n\n**Varn`ya Karma** refers to the complexion-improving effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to improve the complexion and give the skin a healthy glow.\n\n**Vayasthaapana Karma** refers to the age-defying effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to slow down the aging process and keep the skin looking youthful.\n\n**Vran`a Ropan`a Karma** refers to the wound-healing effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to heal wounds and reduce scarring.\n\n**Vran`a S`hodhana Karma** refers to the wound-cleansing effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to cleanse wounds and prevent infection.\n\n**Vrishya Arha Vyaadhi Prakaara** refers to the conditions that are suitable for treatment with Abhyanga. Abhyanga is suitable for a variety of conditions, including headaches, back pain, and insomnia.\n\n**Vaataja Vyaadhi Arha Vyaadhi** refers to the conditions that are caused by an imbalance of the Vata dosha. Abhyanga can be used to balance the Vata dosha and treat conditions such as anxiety, insomnia, and constipation.\n\n**Aalasya Arha Vyaadhi** refers to the condition of laziness. Abhyanga can help to reduce laziness and improve energy levels.\n\n**Aamavaata Arha Vyaadhi** refers to the condition of rheumatoid arthritis. Abhyanga can hel