d S`hodhana Nasya expels the vitiated Dosha out of the body.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dac026bf-a315-4da7-b42f-d71409c0bd1d": {"__data__": {"id_": "dac026bf-a315-4da7-b42f-d71409c0bd1d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"tag": "p", "file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Therapeutic_Procedures/Procedure_Files/Nasya.htm", "file_name": "Nasya.htm", "file_type": "text/html", "file_size": 7464, "creation_date": "2024-02-15", "last_modified_date": "2024-02-14", "last_accessed_date": "2024-02-15", "summary": "Nasya, also known as errhines, refers to the administration of medicine or unctuous substances through the nose. It is a preventive measure, particularly during spring, for healthy individuals using intense drugs. Before the procedure, the patient should be prepared by evacuating bowels, brushing teeth, and receiving medicated smoking. The room should be free of excessive wind and dust. The medicine is prepared according to the subtypes. After the procedure, the patient should avoid cold water contact, dust, fumes, unctuous drugs, sun rays, alcohol, head bath, traveling on fast vehicles, anger, and sleep. Benefits of Nasya include dryness of nose, eyes, and ears; relief from disease; heaviness of body; secretions through nose, eyes, and mouth; and itching. Nasya is classified based on the part of the drug used, the form of the drug, and other factors."}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["tag", "file_path", "file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "245dddb7-a6de-428d-8a4c-c4f884d8eeea", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Th