lead to illness.\n\nVata is the energy of movement and governs the nervous system, circulation, and respiration. Pitta is the energy of digestion and metabolism and governs the digestive system, liver, and gallbladder. Kapha is the energy of structure and governs the bones, muscles, and joints.\n\nAyurvedic practitioners use a variety of methods to diagnose and treat imbalances in the doshas. These methods include taking a patient's history, performing a physical examination, and observing the patient's tongue and pulse. Ayurvedic practitioners may also recommend dietary changes, herbal remedies, massage, or yoga to help balance the doshas and promote health."}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["tag", "file_path", "file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "07b47e72-ad30-4bb9-b176-9efc00bd8ef9", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Therapeutic_Procedures/Procedure_Files/Utkartana.htm", "file_name": "Utkartana.htm", "file_type": "text/html", "file_size": 815, "creation_date": "2024-02-15", "last_modified_date": "2024-02-14", "last_accessed_date": "2024-02-15"}, "hash": "2bfffc3c078c4edf043faf8812da869188c095bfe307e4e214e65eb4be882e34", "class_name": "RelatedNodeInfo"}}, "text": "Ayurveda S`habdakos`ha The procedure in which incision is to be taken at the site of bite by using the specific instrument is termed as Utkartana Chikitsaa Karma: Incision at the site of bite facilitates easier removal of poison by suction. Pradhaanakarma: The site should be incised with a single cut or two cuts crossing each other. Depth and shape of cut should be according to type of snake and site of bite. Other Description: The instruments used for Utkartana are made up of special alloys containing arsenic, antimony etc. collectively these are called as \u2018Karu\u2019.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n", "class_name": "TextNode"}, "__type__": "1"}, "902cbcaa-e9f5-4477-ab5d-84d71cff6340": {"__data__": {"id_": "902cbcaa-e9f5-4477-ab5d-84d71cff6340", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"tag": "p", "file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Therapeutic_Procedures/Procedure_Files/Utsaadana.htm", "file_name": "Utsaadana.htm", "file_type": "text/html", "file_size": 1268, "creation_date": "2024-02-15", "last_modified_date": "2024-02-14", "last_accessed_date": "2024-02-15", "summary": "Ayurveda, an ancient Indian medical system, emphasizes wound healing by elevating the wound bed (Vran`atala). This procedure is particularly beneficial when the wound is clean, has good granulation, and no discharge, but healing is slow. The absence of diabetes or leprosy and deep wounds are also indications for this procedure. Ayurveda practitioners believe that a deficiency of Maamsa Dhaatu (muscle tissue) contributes to slow healing, so treatments include Maamsarasa (muscle extract) and other recipes rich in Maamsa. Specifically, the Upalepana Karma of Maamsa Dhaatu, which involves applying a paste made from muscle tissue, is recommended to promote healing."}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": ["tag", "file_path", "file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": ["file_name", "file_type", "file_size", "creation_date", "last_modified_date", "last_accessed_date"], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "255a63ed-70d9-4154-907d-c8f52fed07ce", "node_type": "4", "metadata": {"file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Therapeutic_Procedures/Procedure_Files/Utsaadana.htm", "file_name": "Utsaadana.htm", "file_type": "text/html", "file_size": 1268, "creation_date": "2024-02-15", "last_modified_date": "2024-02-14", "last_acces