a** is a type of Ayurvedic treatment that involves applying heat to the body. It is believed to improve circulation, reduce inflammation, and promote sweating. Deepaka can be used to treat a variety of conditions, such as colds, flu, and bronchitis.\n\n**Taila Paatra** is a type of Ayurvedic instrument that is used to apply oil to the body. It is typically made of metal or glass and has a spout that allows for precise application.\n\n**Vastra Gun`a** refers to the qualities of the cloth that is used for Abhyanga. The cloth should be soft, absorbent, and comfortable to wear.\n\n**Drava Gun`a** refers to the qualities of the oil that is used for Abhyanga. The oil should be warm, nourishing, and appropriate for the individual's constitution.\n\n**Snigdha Gun`a** refers to the oily or unctuous quality of the oil that is used for Abhyanga. The oil should be able to penetrate the skin and nourish the tissues.\n\n**Sookshma Gun`a** refers to the fine or subtle quality of the oil that is used for Abhyanga. The oil should be able to penetrate the skin and reach the deeper tissues.\n\n**Sthira Gun`a** refers to the stable or firm quality of the oil that is used for Abhyanga. The oil should not be too thin or too thick, and it should be able to stay on the skin for a period of time.\n\n**Ushn`a Karma** refers to the heating effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to improve circulation and reduce inflammation.\n\n**Balya Karma** refers to the strengthening effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to strengthen the muscles and joints, and it can also improve overall vitality.\n\n**Jvarahara Karma** refers to the fever-reducing effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to reduce fever by promoting sweating.\n\n**Maardavakara Karma** refers to the softening effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to soften the skin and reduce dryness.\n\n**Nidraakara Karma** refers to the sleep-inducing effect of Abhyanga. Abhyanga can help to promote relaxation and sleep.\n\n**Preen`ana Karma** refers to t