status is also examined to determine the appropriate time for the procedure.\n\nDuring the procedure, a thick paste made from black gram or barley flour is applied around the eye to create a seal. The unctuous material, such as ghee or medicated milk, is then poured into the flour wall and retained for a prescribed period of time. The patient is instructed to blink and move their eyes slowly throughout the session.\n\nAfter the prescribed time, the ghee is drained and the flour paste is gently removed. The eye is then cleaned with a soft, moist cloth. The patient is advised to rest and avoid exposure to bright light immediately after the procedure.\n\nTarpan`a is beneficial for conditions such as Timira (cataracts), Naktaandhya (night blindness), and difficulty in opening the eyes. It is also effective in reducing eye fatigue and restoring eye function to normal."}}, "8f5d6e8c-8066-4f1e-8ed9-814bb0e77f7a": {"node_ids": ["96f79e11-44bb-4d2e-8c3d-7a88a23193b0"], "metadata": {"tag": "p", "file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Therapeutic_Procedures/Procedure_Files/Nirooha Basti.htm", "file_name": "Nirooha Basti.htm", "file_type": "text/html", "file_size": 17105, "creation_date": "2024-02-15", "last_modified_date": "2024-02-14", "last_accessed_date": "2024-02-15", "summary": "**Summary of the Text**\n\n**Nirooha Basti:**\n\n* A type of enema where medicine is administered into the rectum using an animal's bladder.\n* Predominantly uses decoction as the base liquid.\n* Helps expel Doshas (toxins) from the body.\n* Can be administered to patients of any age.\n\n**Procedure:**\n\n* Patient is positioned on their left side with legs in specific positions.\n* The Bastiput`aka (bladder) is filled with lukewarm medicine and attached to the Basti Netra (applicator).\n* The Basti Netra is inserted into the rectum and the medicine is administered steadily.\n* The patient is then positioned to retain the medicine for as long as possible.\n\n**Benefits:**\n\n* Retards aging and improves overall health.\n* Improves digestion and prevents Aama (toxins) formation.\n* Cleanses the colon and eliminates waste.\n* Tones muscles and improves physical strength.\n* Balances Doshas and treats various diseases.\n\n**Complications:**\n\n* Can arise due to issues with the Bastiput`aka, Basti Netra, or administration technique.\n* Symptoms include fatigue, abdominal distension, and headache.\n\n**Dosage:**\n\n* Varies according to the patient's age.\n* For children, the dose increases by half a Prasriti each year until age 12.\n* For adults, the dose increases by one Prasriti each year until age 18 and remains constant until age 70.\n\n**Combination with Other Basti Types:**\n\n* Nirooha Basti should be administered alternately with Anurta Basti (another type of enema) to counterbalance effects and maintain equilibrium."}}, "8fca0bf7-9ece-4e1c-87e4-d153462a308d": {"node_ids": ["8d4d006e-f4b2-48cf-8767-c8bf30094708"], "metadata": {"tag": "p", "file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Therapeutic_Procedures/Procedure_Files/Nirvaapan`a.htm", "file_name": "Nirvaapan`a.htm", "file_type": "text/html", "file_size": 679, "creation_date": "2024-02-15", "last_modified_date": "2024-02-14", "last_accessed_date": "2024-02-15", "summary": "Nirvaapan is a treatment method in Ayurveda that involves applying or sprinkling cold substances (Dravya) over a wound to provide a cooling effect. The Dravya is typically macerated with cow's milk and ghee, and applied as a cold, moderately thick paste. Alternatively, a decoction of the Dravya can be used for sprinkling, similar to using ice-cold water or Amla Kaanji. Specific indications and formulations for Nirvaapan can be found using the Anveshak search facility."}}, "8a17d9f0-427c-492f-b9b5-09d097679be0": {"node_ids": ["72cd29c5-8819-4688-9e8f-181ed2c67320"], "metadata": {"tag": "p", "file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Therapeutic_Procedures/Procedure_Files/Nishpeed`ana.htm", "file_name": "Nishpeed`ana.htm", "file_