na Krama is tailored to the intensity of the Panchakarma treatment. For milder treatments, Peya, Vilepi, Akrita Yoosha, Krita Yoosha, Akrita Maamsa Rasa, and Krita Maamsa Rasa are introduced in that order. For more intense treatments, the sequence may include additional steps.\n\nAkrita preparations are made without spices or seasonings, while Krita preparations include spices and seasonings to enhance taste and digestibility. Maamsa Rasa is a meat soup that can be consumed on its own or used as a base for other dishes."}}, "ac74a90e-4952-4d95-bd2d-a4be736c8f47": {"node_ids": ["aa2dacd0-2312-43db-a879-08ad132dca8b"], "metadata": {"tag": "p", "file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Therapeutic_Procedures/Procedure_Files/Sandhaana.htm", "file_name": "Sandhaana.htm", "file_type": "text/html", "file_size": 739, "creation_date": "2024-02-15", "last_modified_date": "2024-02-14", "last_accessed_date": "2024-02-15", "summary": "Sure, here is a summary of the information provided in the reference passage:\n\n* **Sandhaana** is the approximation of wound edges and the process to control bleeding.\n* **Pradhaanakarma** is the main procedure for achieving Sandhaana.\n* **Seevana** (suturing) is the main Pradhaanakarma for Sandhaana.\n* When suturing is not possible, the wound edges should be approximated and **Bandha** (bandage) should be applied.\n* If **Maamsa** (flesh) is protruding through the wound, it should be cut before approximation.\n* The tying of **bleeders** (blood vessels) in surgical procedures to control bleeding also comes under Sandhaana.\n\nIn simple terms, Sandhaana is the process of closing a wound and controlling bleeding. This can be done through suturing, bandaging, or other methods."}}, "9f1f3983-714a-4b59-9f03-0bdcb7004152": {"node_ids": ["91c8b3b5-b13e-4344-93ae-620607114bdd"], "metadata": {"tag": "p", "file_path": "/home/dai/rag/data/clean_html/Therapeutic_Procedures/Procedure_Files/Sankara Sveda.htm", "file_name": "Sankara Sveda.htm", "file_type